# Web Development Standards for Rails 8 + Hotwire + TailwindCSS

You are an expert in Ruby on Rails 8, Hotwire (Turbo + Stimulus), TailwindCSS, and modern web application development.

## Core Tech Stack

- Ruby 3.4+
- Ruby on Rails 8.0+
- Hotwire (Turbo + Stimulus)
- TailwindCSS 3.x
- SQLite3 (production-ready with Rails 8)
- Propshaft (default asset pipeline)
- Importmap (JavaScript management)

## Rails 8 Specific Features

- **Authentication Generator**: Use `rails generate authentication` for session-based authentication
- **Solid Queue**: Default background job processor (replaces Sidekiq/Resque)
- **Solid Cache**: Database-backed caching (replaces Redis)
- **Solid Cable**: Database-backed WebSocket adapter for Action Cable
- **Propshaft**: Default asset pipeline (replaces Sprockets)
- **Kamal 2**: Deployment configuration included by default

## Architecture Principles

### Strict Rails Conventions
- Follow MVC pattern rigidly: Models contain business logic, Views handle presentation, Controllers coordinate
- RESTful routing is mandatory - use standard REST actions (index, show, new, create, edit, update, destroy)
- Convention over Configuration - follow Rails defaults unless absolutely necessary
- DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself) - extract repeated code into helpers, partials, or concerns
- KISS (Keep It Simple, Stupid) - always choose the simplest solution

### Desktop-First Responsive Design
- Primary target: 1280px (desktop)
- Tablet: 768px (use `md:` prefix)
- Mobile: 375px (use `sm:` prefix)
- Always write desktop styles first, then scale down with responsive prefixes

## File Structure & Naming

### Models
- File: singular, snake_case (`user.rb`, `blog_post.rb`)
- Class: singular, PascalCase (`User`, `BlogPost`)
- Table: plural, snake_case (`users`, `blog_posts`)

### Controllers
- File: plural, snake_case with `_controller.rb` suffix (`users_controller.rb`)
- Class: plural, PascalCase with `Controller` suffix (`UsersController`)
- Keep actions under 10 lines
- Maximum 2 instance variables per action

### Views
- Directory: plural, snake_case (`app/views/users/`)
- Files: action name, snake_case (`index.html.erb`, `show.html.erb`)
- Partials: start with underscore (`_form.html.erb`, `_user_card.html.erb`)
- Use `app/views/shared/` for cross-controller partials

### Stimulus Controllers
- File: snake_case with `_controller.js` suffix (`dropdown_controller.js`)
- Location: `app/javascript/controllers/`
- HTML identifier: kebab-case (`data-controller="dropdown"`)

## ID Naming Strategy

IDs are critical for debugging, JavaScript targeting, and maintainability. Use clear, descriptive, natural language IDs.

### ID Naming Patterns

**General Format**: `[context]-[element]-[purpose]`

**Forms & Inputs**:
```html
<!-- Form containers -->
<form id="user-login-form">
<form id="article-edit-form">
<form id="comment-create-form">

<!-- Input fields -->
<input id="user-email-input" type="email">
<input id="user-password-input" type="password">
<input id="article-title-input" type="text">
<textarea id="article-body-textarea"></textarea>

<!-- Submit buttons -->
<button id="login-submit-button" type="submit">
<button id="save-draft-button" type="button">
```

**Navigation Elements**:
```html
<!-- Main navigation -->
<nav id="main-navigation">
<nav id="mobile-navigation">
<nav id="user-account-menu">

<!-- Navigation items -->
<a id="nav-home-link" href="/">
<a id="nav-articles-link" href="/articles">
<button id="mobile-menu-toggle-button">
```

**Content Sections**:
```html
<!-- Page sections -->
<div id="hero-section">
<div id="user-dashboard-container">
<div id="article-list-section">
<div id="comments-section">

<!-- Specific content areas -->
<div id="user-profile-header">
<div id="article-metadata-panel">
<div id="sidebar-widget-container">
```

**Interactive Components**:
```html
<!-- Modals -->
<div id="delete-confirmation-modal">
<div id="user-settings-modal">
<div id="image-preview-modal">

<!-- Dropdowns -->
<div id="user-menu-dropdown">
<div id="sort-options-dropdown">

<!-- Tabs -->
<div id="profile-tabs-container">
<button id="profile-overview-tab">
<button id="profile-settings-tab">

<!-- Dynamic content -->
<div id="notification-badge">
<div id="search-results-container">
<div id="loading-spinner">
```

**Stimulus Targets** (prefer data-targets, but when IDs needed):
```html
<!-- When ID is needed for both Stimulus and other purposes -->
<div data-controller="dropdown" id="user-dropdown-container">
  <button data-action="dropdown#toggle" id="user-dropdown-toggle">
  <div data-dropdown-target="menu" id="user-dropdown-menu">
</div>
```

**Debugging-Friendly Patterns**:
```html
<!-- Bad: Cryptic IDs -->
<div id="d1">
<div id="container2">
<button id="btn">

<!-- Good: Self-documenting IDs -->
<div id="user-profile-container">
<div id="article-comments-container">
<button id="edit-profile-button">
```

### ID Naming Rules

1. **Always use kebab-case**: `user-profile-form` not `userProfileForm` or `user_profile_form`
2. **Be specific**: `user-login-form` not just `form`
3. **Include context**: `article-title-input` not just `title`
4. **Use purpose suffixes**:
   - `-container` for wrapper divs
   - `-section` for major page sections
   - `-button` for buttons
   - `-input` for input fields
   - `-link` for links
   - `-modal` for modals
   - `-dropdown` for dropdowns
   - `-menu` for menus
   - `-panel` for panels/cards
5. **Prefix with resource name**: `user-`, `article-`, `comment-` when relevant
6. **Never use generic IDs**: Avoid `id="container"`, `id="wrapper"`, `id="button"`
7. **Use sparingly**: Only add IDs when needed for:
   - Form label associations
   - JavaScript/Stimulus targeting
   - Deep linking/anchors
   - CSS styling (when classes won't work)

## Ruby & Rails Code Standards

### Controllers

```ruby
class ArticlesController < ApplicationController
  # Always use before_action for authentication/authorization
  before_action :require_login
  before_action :set_article, only: [:show, :edit, :update, :destroy]
  
  def index
    @articles = Article.published.recent.limit(20)
  end
  
  def create
    @article = Article.new(article_params)
    
    if @article.save
      redirect_to @article, notice: "Article created successfully."
    else
      render :new, status: :unprocessable_entity
    end
  end
  
  private
  
  def set_article
    @article = Article.find(params[:id])
  end
  
  # Always use strong parameters
  def article_params
    params.require(:article).permit(:title, :body, :status)
  end
end
```

**Controller Rules**:
- Keep actions under 10 lines
- Use `before_action` for common logic
- Always use strong parameters
- Set proper HTTP status codes (`:unprocessable_entity` for validation errors)
- Use `redirect_to` for successful actions, `render` for errors
- Maximum 2 instance variables per action

### Models

```ruby
class Article < ApplicationRecord
  # 1. Constants
  STATUSES = ['draft', 'published', 'archived'].freeze
  
  # 2. Associations (belongs_to first, then has_many/has_one)
  belongs_to :user
  has_many :comments, dependent: :destroy
  has_many :tags, through: :article_tags
  
  # 3. Validations
  validates :title, presence: true, length: { minimum: 5, maximum: 200 }
  validates :body, presence: true, length: { minimum: 100 }
  validates :status, inclusion: { in: STATUSES }
  validates :slug, uniqueness: { scope: :user_id, case_sensitive: false }
  
  # 4. Scopes
  scope :published, -> { where(status: 'published') }
  scope :recent, -> { order(created_at: :desc) }
  scope :popular, -> { where('views_count > ?', 1000) }
  
  # 5. Callbacks (use sparingly)
  before_validation :generate_slug
  before_save :sanitize_title
  
  # 6. Public methods
  def publish!
    update!(status: 'published', published_at: Time.current)
  end
  
  def draft?
    status == 'draft'
  end
  
  # 7. Private methods
  private
  
  def generate_slug
    self.slug = title.parameterize if title.present?
  end
  
  def sanitize_title
    self.title = title.strip
  end
end
```

**Model Rules**:
- Always follow order: constants, associations, validations, scopes, callbacks, public methods, private methods
- Put `belongs_to` before `has_many`/`has_one`
- Always specify `dependent:` option on associations (`:destroy`, `:delete_all`, or `:nullify`)
- Use `!` suffix for methods that raise exceptions (`save!`, `update!`, `publish!`)
- Use `?` suffix for boolean methods (`draft?`, `active?`, `expired?`)
- Avoid callbacks - use service objects for complex logic
- Keep models under 200 lines

### Migrations

```ruby
class CreateArticles < ActiveRecord::Migration[8.0]
  def change
    create_table :articles do |t|
      t.string :title, null: false
      t.text :body, null: false
      t.string :slug, null: false
      t.string :status, default: 'draft', null: false
      t.integer :views_count, default: 0, null: false
      t.references :user, null: false, foreign_key: true
      t.datetime :published_at
      
      t.timestamps
    end
    
    # Always add indexes for foreign keys and frequently queried columns
    add_index :articles, :slug, unique: true
    add_index :articles, :status
    add_index :articles, :published_at
    add_index :articles, [:user_id, :status]
  end
end
```

**Migration Rules**:
- Always include `null:` constraint (use `null: false` for required fields)
- Always include `default:` for boolean and enum fields
- Always use `t.timestamps` (creates `created_at` and `updated_at`)
- Use `t.references` for foreign keys (automatically adds index and type)
- Add `foreign_key: true` to maintain referential integrity
- Add indexes for:
  - Foreign keys (automatic with `t.references`)
  - Frequently queried columns
  - Unique columns
  - Composite indexes for multi-column queries
- Never edit `schema.rb` directly
- Never delete old migrations

### Routes

```ruby
# config/routes.rb

Rails.application.routes.draw do
  # Root route
  root "articles#index"
  
  # Standard RESTful resources
  resources :articles do
    # Nested resources (max 1 level deep)
    resources :comments, only: [:create, :destroy]
    
    # Member routes (act on single resource)
    member do
      post :publish
      post :archive
    end
    
    # Collection routes (act on collection)
    collection do
      get :drafts
    end
  end
  
  # Shallow nesting for nested resources
  resources :users do
    resources :articles, shallow: true
  end
  
  # Custom routes (avoid when possible)
  get '/about', to: 'pages#about'
  
  # Health check endpoint
  get "up" => "rails/health#show", as: :rails_health_check
end
```

**Routing Rules**:
- Always use `resources` for RESTful routes
- Nest resources maximum 1 level deep
- Use `shallow: true` for deeper nesting
- Use `only:` or `except:` to limit routes
- Use `member` for single-resource actions
- Use `collection` for collection actions
- Avoid custom routes unless absolutely necessary

## Hotwire (Turbo + Stimulus)

### Turbo Frames

```erb
<!-- List page with turbo frame -->
<%= turbo_frame_tag "articles" do %>
  <div id="articles-list-container">
    <%= render @articles %>
  </div>
<% end %>

<!-- Individual article partial -->
<%= turbo_frame_tag dom_id(article) do %>
  <article id="<%= "article-#{article.id}-container" %>">
    <h2><%= article.title %></h2>
    <%= link_to "Edit", edit_article_path(article) %>
  </article>
<% end %>
```

**Turbo Frame Rules**:
- Use `turbo_frame_tag` with unique IDs
- Use `dom_id(record)` helper for model-based frames
- Use `data-turbo-frame="_top"` to break out of frame
- Target frames with `data-turbo-frame="frame_id"`
- Keep frame interactions simple

### Turbo Streams

```ruby
# Controller
def create
  @comment = @article.comments.build(comment_params)
  
  respond_to do |format|
    if @comment.save
      format.turbo_stream
      format.html { redirect_to @article }
    else
      format.turbo_stream { render turbo_stream: turbo_stream.replace("comment_form", partial: "form", locals: { comment: @comment }) }
      format.html { render :new, status: :unprocessable_entity }
    end
  end
end
```

```erb
<!-- app/views/comments/create.turbo_stream.erb -->
<%= turbo_stream.prepend "comments-list", @comment %>
<%= turbo_stream.replace "comment-form" do %>
  <%= render "comments/form", article: @article, comment: Comment.new %>
<% end %>
```

**Turbo Stream Rules**:
- Always provide `format.html` fallback
- Use stream actions: `append`, `prepend`, `replace`, `update`, `remove`
- Name files: `action.turbo_stream.erb`
- Target elements by ID (not class)

### Stimulus Controllers

```javascript
// app/javascript/controllers/dropdown_controller.js

import { Controller } from "@hotwired/stimulus"

export default class extends Controller {
  static targets = ["menu", "button"]
  static classes = ["open", "closed"]
  static values = {
    openDuration: { type: Number, default: 300 }
  }
  
  connect() {
    // Runs when controller connects to DOM
    console.log("Dropdown controller connected")
  }
  
  disconnect() {
    // Cleanup when controller disconnects
  }
  
  toggle() {
    if (this.menuTarget.classList.contains(this.openClass)) {
      this.close()
    } else {
      this.open()
    }
  }
  
  open() {
    this.menuTarget.classList.remove(this.closedClass)
    this.menuTarget.classList.add(this.openClass)
  }
  
  close() {
    this.menuTarget.classList.remove(this.openClass)
    this.menuTarget.classList.add(this.closedClass)
  }
  
  // Close dropdown when clicking outside
  hide(event) {
    if (!this.element.contains(event.target)) {
      this.close()
    }
  }
}
```

```html
<!-- HTML usage -->
<div data-controller="dropdown"
     data-action="click@window->dropdown#hide"
     data-dropdown-open-class="block"
     data-dropdown-closed-class="hidden"
     id="user-menu-dropdown">
  <button data-action="dropdown#toggle"
          data-dropdown-target="button"
          id="user-menu-toggle-button">
    Menu
  </button>
  <div data-dropdown-target="menu"
       class="hidden"
       id="user-menu-dropdown-menu">
    <!-- menu items -->
  </div>
</div>
```

**Stimulus Rules**:
- One controller per behavior (dropdown, modal, autosave, etc.)
- Use `static targets` to reference DOM elements
- Use `static values` for dynamic data (URLs, IDs, options)
- Use `static classes` for CSS class names
- Use `data-action` for event binding
- Format: `event->controller#action` or `event@window->controller#action`
- Keep controllers under 200 lines
- Export as default: `export default class extends Controller`

